## GitHub Actions: 49. Matrix Strategy in GitHub Actions

**Matrix Strategy** is used to run the same job multiple times with different values.

Example:

Run tests on:

✅ Different Java versions
✅ Different Node.js versions
✅ Different operating systems
✅ Different browsers
✅ Different environments

## Why use Matrix Strategy?

Matrix strategy helps to test our application in multiple combinations automatically.

Example:

```text
Java 17 on Ubuntu
Java 21 on Ubuntu
Java 17 on Windows
Java 21 on Windows
```

Instead of writing separate jobs, we use one matrix job.

## Basic Syntax

```yaml
strategy:
  matrix:
    java-version: [17, 21]
```

Then use it like this:

```yaml
${{ matrix.java-version }}
```

## Example: Java Maven Project with Matrix Strategy

Create file:

```text
.github/workflows/matrix-java.yml
```

```yaml
name: Java Matrix Build

on:
  push:
    branches: [ main ]

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    strategy:
      matrix:
        java-version: [17, 21]

    steps:
      - name: Checkout Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Setup Java
        uses: actions/setup-java@v4
        with:
          distribution: temurin
          java-version: ${{ matrix.java-version }}

      - name: Build with Maven
        run: mvn clean install
```

## Explanation

This workflow runs the same build job two times:

```text
Run 1 → Java 17
Run 2 → Java 21
```

So we can confirm our project works on both Java versions.

## Example: Matrix with Operating Systems

```yaml
name: OS Matrix Build

on: push

jobs:
  test:
    runs-on: ${{ matrix.os }}

    strategy:
      matrix:
        os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest, macos-latest]
        java-version: [17, 21]

    steps:
      - name: Checkout Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Setup Java
        uses: actions/setup-java@v4
        with:
          distribution: temurin
          java-version: ${{ matrix.java-version }}

      - name: Run Tests
        run: mvn test
```

## How many jobs will run?

Matrix creates combinations:

```text
3 operating systems × 2 Java versions = 6 jobs
```

Jobs:

```text
ubuntu-latest + Java 17
ubuntu-latest + Java 21
windows-latest + Java 17
windows-latest + Java 21
macos-latest + Java 17
macos-latest + Java 21
```

## Include Extra Combination

We can add special combinations using `include`.

```yaml
strategy:
  matrix:
    os: [ubuntu-latest]
    java-version: [17]
    include:
      - os: ubuntu-latest
        java-version: 21
```

This runs:

```text
Ubuntu + Java 17
Ubuntu + Java 21
```

## Exclude Combination

We can skip some combinations using `exclude`.

```yaml
strategy:
  matrix:
    os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest]
    java-version: [17, 21]
    exclude:
      - os: windows-latest
        java-version: 21
```

This skips:

```text
Windows + Java 21
```

## Real-Time Use Case

For a company project, before deployment we want to check:

```text
Java 17 and Java 21
Ubuntu and Windows
```

Matrix strategy helps automatically test all combinations without writing multiple jobs manually.

## Full Example with Fail Fast

```yaml
name: Matrix Build with Fail Fast

on: push

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ${{ matrix.os }}

    strategy:
      fail-fast: false
      matrix:
        os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest]
        java-version: [17, 21]

    steps:
      - name: Checkout Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Setup Java
        uses: actions/setup-java@v4
        with:
          distribution: temurin
          java-version: ${{ matrix.java-version }}

      - name: Build Project
        run: mvn clean install
```

## What is `fail-fast: false`?

By default, if one matrix job fails, GitHub may cancel other running jobs.

```yaml
fail-fast: false
```

Means even if one job fails, remaining matrix jobs will continue running.

## Benefits of Matrix Strategy

Saves time.
Reduces duplicate workflow code.
Tests multiple environments.
Improves software quality.
Very useful for CI/CD pipelines.

## Simple Definition

**Matrix Strategy in GitHub Actions means running the same job with multiple values like different Java versions, Node versions, or operating systems automatically.**
